{"key":"post-8540009","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8540009</id>\n<content>You might need to calibrate your hygrometer.&amp;nbsp; Three inches is minimum because air flows up from the bottom and through the perlite.&amp;nbsp; Make sure you have the terrarium sitting on blocks so air can circulate under it, and then up through the holes in the bottom.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, rake the perlite with your fingers to fluff it up every few days.&amp;nbsp; If the perlite settles and packs down, it can't evaporate moisture as easily.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You also want to be misting a few times daily.&amp;nbsp; Misting directly moistens the cakes and what falls on the perlite keeps it moist.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've written up the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium tek&lt;/a&gt; with a section on lighting for those who haven't seen it yet.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>8539668</prev>\n<first>8538718</first>\n<last>8540009</last>\n<when>1213884113</when>\n<utime>06/19/08 05:01 PM</utime>\n</post>"}